Title:
Anti-malware Scan Interface (AMSI) integration with Microsoft Defender Antivirus

Type:
Documentation

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This Microsoft Defender for Endpoint documentation explains how AMSI is used by Microsoft Defender Antivirus to detect fileless and script-based threats by scanning content at execution time.  
- It focuses on how AMSI improves visibility into obfuscated or in-memory payload delivery via built-in Windows scripting hosts (notably PowerShell, WSH, JScript/VBScript) and .NET assembly loads.  
- The article outlines common fileless techniques (reflective DLL injection, memory exploits, script-based loaders, WMI persistence) and maps them to Defender capabilities like script scanning via AMSI, WMI repository scanning, and enhanced memory scanning/behavior monitoring.  
- It lists supported OS versions and scripting/runtime coverage (including Microsoft 365 Apps macro/script surfaces) and notes gaps (no Python/Perl AMSI support).  
- It provides enablement guidance: AMSI protection is effectively enabled by turning on Defender “script scanning” via policy (including MDM Policy CSP).  
- It also points to complementary hardening controls (WDAC/AppLocker with Constrained Language Mode, ASR rules, and HVCI) to reduce fileless attack success.

Technical Focus:
- AMSI content scanning pipeline and Defender script scanning
- PowerShell/WSH/JScript/VBScript inspection and deobfuscation visibility
- .NET assembly scanning (Framework 4.8+) and in-memory execution patterns
- WMI repository scanning and WMI-based persistence detection
- Memory scanning/behavioral detection for reflective injection and kernel-memory threats
- Hardening with WDAC/AppLocker (Constrained Language Mode), ASR, and HVCI

Use Cases:
- Enable/validate AMSI-backed script scanning in Defender-managed Windows fleets
- Assess detection coverage for PowerShell/WSH-based post-exploitation and fileless tradecraft
- Build defensive baselines combining AMSI + WDAC/ASR/HVCI against in-memory loaders
- Identify scripting/runtime blind spots (e.g., Python/Perl) for risk management and monitoring

Keywords:
AMSI, Microsoft Defender Antivirus, Microsoft Defender for Endpoint, script scanning, fileless malware, PowerShell, Windows Script Host, wscript.exe, cscript.exe, JScript, VBScript, .NET Framework 4.8, WMI, WMI persistence, reflective DLL injection, in-memory execution, obfuscation, WDAC, AppLocker, Constrained Language Mode, Attack Surface Reduction, HVCI, virtualization-based security, EternalBlue, DoublePulsar